AB Research and market evidence indicate that positioning a brand as an
   underdog can be an effective marketing strategy. Interestingly, if
   successful, this strategy could result in brands outgrowing their
   underdog status. In such situations, the current research finds it is
   critical for underdogs to be perceived as authentic to maintain
   long-term consumer support. The importance of authenticity is revealed
   by depth interviews with underdog supporters and three experiments. The
   experiments reveal that a successful underdog brand is perceived as more
   authentic and maintains stronger consumer support if the founders do not
   sell out to a larger company (Experiments 1, 2, and 3). This effect is
   robust across "vote-for" and "vote-against" underdogs, and continued
   founder involvement with the company after selling out has limited
   effectiveness for maintaining perceptions of authenticity and consumer
